         <lb/>
         <lb/>
         <head>NOTES <hi rend="small">TO THE </hi>POEM <hi rend="small">OF </hi> THE
                              BROTHERS.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">
                  <lb/>note i.</hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 26—line 20 “ There were two springs
                                   that bubbled <lb/>side by side.” The impressive
                                   circumstance here described, <lb/>actually took place some years
                                   ago in this country, upon an <lb/>eminence called Kidstow Pike,
                                   one of the highest of the <lb/>mountains that surround
                                   Hawes-water. The summit of the <lb/>pike was stricken by
                                   lightning ; and every trace of one of the <lb/>fountains
                                   disappeared, while the other continued to flow as
                                   <lb/>before.</p>
         </div>
         <lb/>
         <div xml:id="note2b">
            <head>
               <hi rend="small">note ii. </hi>
            </head>
            <p rend="note"> Page 29—line 5 “ The thought of death sits
                                   easy on the <lb/>man,” &amp;c. There is not any thing more
                                   worthy of remark <lb/>in the manners of the inhabitants of these
                                   mountains, than <lb/>the tranquillity, I might say indifference,
                                   with which they <lb/>think and talk upon the subject of death.
                                   Some of the coun-<lb/>try church-yards, as here described, do not
                                   contain a single <lb/>tombstone, and most of them have a very
                                   small number.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
